    <title>Combined summary - [BIP/Draft] BIP Acceptance Process</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T22:07:48.910495+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-September/010914.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) process has been a topic of discussion in the Bitcoin community. One proposal suggests creating committees to review and vote on BIPs collectively, while others are concerned about censorship and centralization pressures. Another approach is micro votes, but there are concerns about proving and preventing manipulation. The goal of the proposal is to ensure a fair system for finding "acceptance" of BIPs. However, some argue that market forces should decide instead.The current BIP process lacks transparency, causing confusion and hindering investment. A new BIP process has been suggested that would work alongside the existing one and involve more voices to gain a clearer idea of acceptance. Suggestions have been made for honest but anonymous voting mechanisms. It's important to note that BIPs only communicate technical proposals to the bitcoin community and their implementation in Bitcoin software is not guaranteed.There are debates around how different groups prove their stake and what constitutes "accepted." While Bitcoin Core has a major influence on adoption, it is not the only implementation, and the community at large will decide if it becomes widely adopted. The proposal aims to stimulate ideas on governance regarding the BIP process, and committees should not be introduced into the process.Two individuals, Andy Chase and Luke, have discussed the BIP process and agree that a new proposal is necessary but have different approaches to solving the problem. Luke suggests a specification based on BIP 123 that determines when a proposal is accepted by discernment rather than decision-making. He argues that committees should not be authorized groups, but rather fluid and re-validated for each BIP evaluation. The author argues that attempts to identify individuals in Bitcoin are futile and destructive, supporting the idea of measuring consensus with proto-ideas on how this could be achieved.Criticism has been offered for committee design, and a mandatory requirement for ecosystem echo-chambers to make many attempts and efforts at steelman representations of alternative viewpoints has been proposed. The current system for decision-making in Bitcoin lacks transparency, causing confusion and hindering major players from investing large sums. However, proponents argue that a more consistent and transparent process involving risk matrices would not replace analysis but rather make it more consistent and understandable.Overall, while there are differing opinions on the best approach to improving the BIP process and decision-making in Bitcoin, there is a shared interest in making the process more transparent and consistent. The status of a BIP is determined by its adoption within the community, and while the process may be loose, recent flood of BIPs added with zero bureaucracy or friction shows it's not necessarily broken. Anyone can publish a BIP easily, and whether or not it gets adopted is up to the community.</summary>
